1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 { The Smith-Morra - a gambit that has been popular
with club players for ages as a way to sidestep mainline Open Sicilian theory
while still getting reasonable attacking positions. } { [%cal Gd4c3] } 3... dxc3 (3... Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 { is a transposition I recommended in my 2014 book "The Killer Sicilian". If you
already play 2...Nf6 against the Alapin, this is a very simple and minimalist
way to meet the Smith-Morra. }) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bc4 a6!? { The
so-called Taylor Defense - named after Tim Taylor, who recommended this system
in a book he wrote in the 90's. Since then, it has also been recommended by
Gallagher and Palliser in their respective works as well. This system could
still use some updating in my opinion, and so here we are. Black's main idea
with ...a6 is to prepare ...Nf6 safely. Furthermore, contrary to a lot of
systems against the Morra, Black is very deliberately delaying the move ...e6
(it is very useful indeed - shutting out the Bc4, preparing kingside
development) for a move to ensure that ...Bg4 is still possible. This
development of the light-square bishop outside of the chain is one of the key
features of this system, and one of the main reasons it's so strong against
those players that want to use the Morra as a "system". If White intends to
simply play Bc4, Qe2, Rfd1, etc, against everything, then ...Bg4 can many
times completely shut down the e5-break and also cost White a tempo, as Qe2xf3
is inefficient compared to simply taking on f3 in one move. } (6... Nf6?! { right away is probably not great on account of } 7. e5! dxe5 (7... Ng4 8. exd6 exd6 9. O-O $44 { is probably better but still risky for Black. }) 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. Nb5 $40 { when, we can certainly see the benefit of flicking in ...a6 first! }) 7. O-O (7. Bg5!? { was recommended by Langrock in the first edition of his
Morra book, but not in the second! After } 7... Nf6! (7... Bg4? 8. Qb3! { is probably already stone cold lost for Black - one thing to keep in mind is
that when White doesn't rush to play Qe2, they can always play Qb3 instead! }) 8. Bxf6 gxf6 { we get something like a Classical Rauzer. It's interesting:
White would generally like to work up pressure with Qh5, as with the g-pawn
missing that makes it very hard for Black to castle to either side (the
pressure on f7 or h7, etc). But in the Morra version, White has to find a home
for the knight, which costs time. Additionally without the knight on d4, Black
can always meet Qh5 with ...Qa5!, threatening the trade via a very cute
horizontal geometry. In the similar Classical Sicilian positions, White
generally play Qh5 quicker, and also stop ...Qa5 resources by taking on c6
first. In the Morra positions, this is not possible. } 9. O-O (9. Nh4 { is most
the most popular, but if Qh5 is not possible after this move, then this is
probably not the best square for the knight at all. } 9... e6 10. O-O (10. Qh5 Qa5! { is a very annoying resource for Black. }) 10... Be7! (10... h5!? $146 { is similar to the main line, but you have to feel like h4 is a worse square
for the steed than d4. }) 11. Qh5 Qa5! 12. Nf5!? { of S.Christiani - U.
Kersten, Dresden 2003 is cute and looks dangerous, but after the precise } 12... Rf8! $146 13. Ng7+ Kd8 14. Qxh7 Bd7 { White is in big trouble here - Black will
generally go ...Kc7 and then bring the rooks to the open files on the kingside.
White's pieces are totally uncoordinated and Black is happy to give the pawn
back for the active play on the kingside. }) 9... e6 10. Nd4 { Here, White is
ready to go Nxc6 and Qh5, which would be annoying as ...Qa5 would not be
possible. As such, we can stop White's plans with } 10... h5! { Black is ready to
finish development now with ...Be7, ...Bd7, ...Qb6, etc. } 11. Kh1 Qb6 12. Nb3 Bd7 13. f4 O-O-O $17 { F.Haas - H.Schwing, German Leagues 1998. This looks like
a Rauzer but Black still has an extra pawn. }) (7. e5?! { I first came across
this move when ICC was still the hot place to play on the internet. Alex
Lenderman, a master of the Morra in his own right, absolutely rocked me with
it during a simultaneous exhibition. I accepted the offer on e5, which is
definitely not to be recommended! } { [%cal Ge7e6,Gc6e5] } 7... e6! { is much better, when I think it's
possible that White has chosen to break too early, e.g. } (7... dxe5? 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 (8... Kxd8 9. Ng5 Nh6 10. Bxf7 $14) 9. Nd5 { [%cal Gd5c7] } 9... Ne6 10. Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c8,Gb6a8] } 10... Rb8 11. Nxe5 Nf6 12. Nxf7! Kxf7 13. Bf4 $18 { is the main trick here! } { [%csl Rb8][%cal Rf4b8] }) (7... Nxe5 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. Bxf7+) 8. exd6 (8. Bg5 Qc7 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. O-O h6 11. Bh4 Nge7 12. Ne4 Nf5 $17) (8. Bf4 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 10. Nxe5 f6 11. Nf3 Bd7! 12. O-O e5 $17) (8. O-O dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $17) 8... Bxd6 9. O-O Nf6 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Rd1 Qc7 $15) 7... Nf6 { and now we reach the main tabiya, after which
White has many tries. See the next two chapters. } *


