1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bc4 a6!? 7. O-O Nf6 8. Qe2? (8. h3 { White spends a move to stop ...Bg4. Black's best here is to
just head to Scheveningen like positions up a pawn where, arguing that h3 is
basically a waste of a move. } 8... e6 9. Qe2 Be7 10. Rd1 { [%cal Gb7b5] } 10... Qc7 (10... Bd7 { has
typically been my choice here, but I am not so sure anymore, since } 11. Bf4 b5 12. Bb3 Qb8 13. e5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Bxe5 Qb7 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 { is mostly
forced, and now } { [%cal Gc3d5,Gf6d8] } 17. Ne4 Be7 18. Qd2! { gives White reasonable compensation
here, since Black cannot castle yet. Even worse, } 18... Bc6 { is natural but probably
lost after } 19. Nd6+ Bxd6 20. Qxd6 { , when Rac1-c7 is a big problem. }) (10... b5!? 11. Bb3 Qb6!? { is also interesting, hoping to provoke the suboptimal } 12. Be3 { before going } 12... Qb8 { The Be3 actually mostly just gets in the way. }) 11. Bf4 Ne5 { Black has to plug up the e5-square to avoid the e5-break while very
much behind in development. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc7c4] } 12. Bb3 O-O (12... b5 13. Rac1 Qb8 14. Nd4 O-O { is also a fine way to reach the main tabiya }) 13. Rac1 { [%cal Rc1c7] } 13... Qb8! { Again b8 is the
best square for the queen in this variation. } { [%cal Gf3d4,Gf4g3,Gf2f4] } 14. Nd4 { White centralizes the
knight and starts the somewhat slow process of removing all of the pieces from
the f-file in order to push f4. } (14. g4!? { was tried by Jobava instead in B.
Jobava - F.Rakotomaharo, internet blitz 2021, but after the natural } 14... b5 15. g5 Nfd7 16. Nd4 Bb7 17. Bg3 Nc5 18. Bc2 { the famous Georgian attacking wizard
would have been worse after either } 18... Bxg5 19. f4 Bh6 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Nf3 Bxc1 22. Rxc1 f6 { or the more simple 18...b4. }) 14... Bd7 (14... b5 { is also
reasonable, e.g. } 15. Bg3 Bb7 16. f4 Nc6 { and now in T.Horvath - V.Sramek,
Czech Republic 2021 White tried to mix things up with } 17. Nd5!? { but should
still be worse after } 17... exd5 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Rxc6 dxe4 20. Bh4 { after the very
accurate } 20... Qe8! 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Rcxd6 Rd8 23. Rxd8 Bxd8 $15) 15. Bg3 Nc6 16. Nxc6 (16. Nf3 b5 17. e5 dxe5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Bxe5 Qb7 $17 { reaches a
position similar to that demonstrated after 10...Bd7, except that ...O-O and
Rac1 are inserted, which must favor Black, who desperately needs a safer king. }) 16... Bxc6 17. e5 dxe5 18. Bxe5 Qe8 { [%cal Ga8d8] } 19. Rd3 Rd8 20. Rg3 g6 21. Qe3 Nd7 22. Bd4 e5! 23. Bxe5 Nxe5 24. Qxe5 Bd6 25. Qxe8 Rfxe8 26. Rg4 Be5 $17 { Black was
much better in T.Lochte - S.Mooser, German Leagues 2003 } { [%csl Ge5,Gc6][%cal Bd8d2] }) (8. e5? { now just
does not work at all now that b5 and d5 are both covered from knight hops. You
just need to remember to not take on e5 with the knight and you're set. } 8... dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 10. Nxe5 Be6 11. Be2 (11. Rd1) 11... g6 $15 { M.Clancy - R.Haria, British
Championships 2014. I don't think that White has enough compensation for the
pawn here. It's hard to prevent Black from playing ...Bg7 and castling, after
which the second player can usually find ways to trade off some pieces. }) (8. Bf4! { is probably the best move, and is covered in the next file. }) (8. b4!? e6 9. b5 axb5 10. Nxb5 Be7 11. Bf4 Nxe4 12. Re1 O-O! 13. Rxe4 d5 $15) 8... Bg4! 9. Rd1 { [%cal Re4e5] } 9... e6 10. Bf4? { This move, preparing e5 and increasing the pressure
on d6, is the most popular here by far but probably also just straight up
losing. It's not easy to prove however, and the complications and attacking
ideas are actually pretty amazing. } { [%cal Gf6h5,Gd8b8] } (10. h3 { is possibly a better option, but
Black is still better after } 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 (11. gxf3) 11... Be7 12. Bf4 { and now the key move } 12... Qb8! { Boom! All at once, Black removes the queen from the d-file
(eliminating the Rd1 pin) and adds another attacker to the e5-square. Now ...
Ne5 is possible to counteract the pressure on d6, and Black is free to finish
development. A few examples from practice to round out the coverage: } 13. g4 (13. Rd2 { is perhaps the most straightforward, but not impressive, e.g. } 13... O-O 14. Rad1 Ne5 15. Qe2 (15. Bxe5? dxe5 16. g4 Qc7 17. Bb3 Rad8 $19 { J.Mantau - M.
Haag, German Leagues 2010 }) 15... b5 16. Bb3 { [%cal Gb8b7] } 16... Rc8 17. Bh2 { V.Mikhailovsky - R.
Schrik, internet blitz 2020 and now many moves are good, for instance } 17... Qb7 (17... Qb6 $146 18. Kh1 g5!? $17 { is more wild but shows what's possible -
Black stops f4 for good, and because of the Nf6/Ne5 constellation, it's
actually remarkably difficult for White to assault the g-pawn. }) 18. a3 Rc7 $17 { [%cal Ga8c8] }) (13. Qd3 { [%csl Rd6] } 13... Ne5 14. Qe2 O-O 15. Bb3 b5 16. Rac1 Qb7 $17 { V.Kameswara Rao - M.
Erdogdu, Al Ain 2013 }) 13... O-O 14. g5 Nd7 15. Qg3 Nde5 16. Bb3 b5 17. h4 { L.Langner - M.Erdogdu, internet blitz 2020 } 17... Qb7! $17 { [%cal Gc6a5,Ba5c4,Ba5b3,Ga8c8] }) 10... Nh5! { White
can no longer stop ...Ne5, which is a real problem. } { [%csl Gf3] } (10... Qb8!? { is very
much thematic and also strong here for those that want to avoid the
complications after 10...Nh5. } 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Be7 $17 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge8g8,Gc6e5,Gb7b5] }) 11. Be3 (11. Bg3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 h5! $40) 11... Ne5 { White can't stop the fracturing of his kingside pawn structure. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gg2f3,Gc4b3] } 12. Bb3 (12. Qf1 { is the first choice of engines, but it's not a very human choice, as } 12... Nxf3+ 13. gxf3 Bxf3 { is easy to find and terrible for White. Black is up two
pawns AND has the compensation! }) 12... Bxf3 (12... Be7!? { is a little more
simple in a way - Black just plans to dominate on the dark squares, for
instance after ...Bxf3 and ...Bg5. Black can settle either piece into f4 and
the queen somewhere on the kingside with complete domination. } 13. Ba4+ Kf8 (13... b5? 14. Nxb5 axb5 15. Qxb5+ Nd7 16. Bb6 $18) 14. Kh1 Bxf3 15. gxf3 g5 $19 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Ge5g6,Ye7f6,Gh5f4,Gg6f4,Yf6e5,Rh7h6,Rh6h5,Rh5h4] }) 13. gxf3 Qh4 { The threat of ...Qh3 is grave. } { [%cal Gh4h3,Ge5f3] } 14. Kh1 { This is perhaps
the most sensible human defense, planning to defend h2 via Rg1-g2. } (14. Ba4+ { looks enticing, because Black's king is not safe either, but if Black decides
to dive in deep and grab the a8-rook, his own king perishes, for instance } 14... b5 15. Nxb5 axb5 16. Qxb5+ (16. Bxb5+ Ke7 17. Kh1) 16... Ke7 17. Qb7+ Kf6 18. Qxa8 Qh3 19. Kh1 Nxf3 20. Bd4+ e5 21. Bxe5+ dxe5 22. Qd8+ Be7 23. Rd6+ Kg5 24. Qxe7+ f6 25. Rg1+ Kh6 26. Rg2 Nh4! $19 27. Rg4 Qf1+ 28. Rg1 Ng3+ 29. fxg3 (29. hxg3 Qh3#) 29... Qf3+ 30. Rg2 Qxg2#) (14. Nb5 axb5 (14... Rd8 15. Nd4 Be7 $19) 15. Qxb5+ Ke7 16. Qxb7+ Kf6 17. Qxa8 Qh3 18. Kh1 Qxf3+ 19. Kg1 Qh3 20. Kh1 Be7!! 21. Qxh8 Ng4 22. Kg1 Nxe3 23. fxe3 Qxe3+ 24. Kf1 Nf4 25. Bc4 Nh3 26. Kg2 Qf2+ 27. Kxh3 Qf3+ 28. Kh4 Kg6#) 14... Qh3 15. Rg1 g5!! { Brilliant - Black ensures that the g-file opens,
which makes White's planned defense of h2 impossible, as an eventual ...Rg8
breaks everything open. } (15... Nxf3? 16. Rg2 $13) 16. Rxg5 (16. Bxg5 h6 17. Be3 Nxf3 18. Rg2 Rg8 19. Qf1 Rg4! $19) 16... Nxf3 { [%csl Gg5,Gh2] } 17. Rg2 (17. Rxh5 Qxh5 18. Bf4 $19) 17... Rg8 18. Qf1 Rg4! $19 { Beautiful! White is completely tied down, and has no way to stop ...Rh4 and ..
.Qxh2, with mate to follow. } { [%cal Gg4h4,Gh3h2] } *


