1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bc4 a6!? 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bf4! { This move, recommended by both Esserman and Langrock in their
respective books, is likely best. White hopes to reach a tempo up version of
the 8.Qe2 lines by allowing ...Bg4 and recapturing on f3 without having spent
a move on the e2 pitstop. } 8... e6!? { This move, forgoing ...Bg4 entirely, seems
prudent now. It's relatively easy to play and understand, and is less risky
than 8...Bg4, though admittedly both are of equivalent value. } (8... Bg4 { is also possible, but I have found out first hand that these positions can be
a bit trickier, e.g. } 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 e6 11. Rfd1 Qb8 (11... Qa5!? { is the way if you must play 8...Bg4, as } 12. Be2 (12. Bxd6?? Bxd6 13. Rxd6 Ne5 14. Qe2 Qc5 $19) 12... Be7 13. Bxd6 (13. Qg3 { this is Langrock's suggestion,
but I am not sure it's all that great for White after } 13... O-O 14. a3 (14. Rxd6 e5 (14... Bxd6 15. Bxd6 Rfc8 16. e5 Ne8)) 14... Ne5! 15. b4 Qc7 16. Rac1 Qb8 { when Black has avoiding major problems with their kingside
and can continue with ...Rc8 next. }) (13. Rxd6 e5 14. Rxf6 Nd4 15. Qd3 Bxf6 { [%csl Gd4] }) 13... Bxd6 14. Rxd6 O-O 15. Rad1 Rfd8) 12. Be2! { This is a key detail here - White removes the bishop from the
vulnerable c4-square and plays Qg3 without allowing ...Nh5. This is
practically very annoying, and it gets even trickier after } 12... Be7 13. Qg3 O-O 14. Rxd6!? { , since } 14... Bxd6 15. Bxd6 Qa7 16. e5 Nd7 17. Rd1 $40 { of P.Scott - A.
Waller, Correspondence 2018, gives White tremendous play for the exchange. }) 9. Qe2 Nh5! { Unmentioned by Langrock (and also Esserman, but frankly his book
is tough to navigate on my phone and so perhaps I missed his coverage!), Black
tickles the bishop off of the critical h2-b8 diagonal. } (9... Be7 10. Rfd1 Qc7 11. Rac1 O-O 12. Bb3 Qb8 { and now both 13.Na4 or 13.e5 are moderately annoying
though not necessarily bad for Black. }) 10. Be3 Be7 11. Rfd1 Bd7 { and now
White has a wide variety of options: } 12. Nd4 { [%csl Gh5,Gd4] } (12. Rac1 { White has scored 0/5
from this position in my database. That is probably extreme, but Black should
generally be a little better here, e.g. } 12... O-O 13. Bb3 Nf6 14. Bf4 e5 15. Bg5 { [%csl Gd5] } 15... Be6 (15... Bg4! { is also natural and very good. Perhaps White even has to pop
back with 16.Be3 here, and for that reason I might prefer that to Mirzoev's
move. } { [%cal Gc6d4,Gg5e3] }) 16. h3 Rc8 17. Rc2 h6 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nd5 Bg5 { was R.Dongre - A.
Mirzoev, Kolkata 2000. This position very much looks like a Kalashnikov
Sicilian, but White is down a pawn for a small amount of positional control. I
tend to think that maybe Black is a tiny bit better here, but it's not much. } { [%cal Gc6a5] }) (12. e5? dxe5 13. Na4 { looks dangerous, but doesn't quite work after } 13... Nf4! 14. Qd2 Nd5! { when Black chucks one of his two pawns back in order to grab a
bishop and quench White's initiative somewhat, for example } { [%cal Ra4b6,Gd5b6,Gd5e3] } 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Qxd5 (16. Nb6? d4 { is also better for Black }) 16... Be6 17. Qe4 Qa5! { getting ready to castle and planning to meet Bb6 with either ...Qb5 or ...Qb4. } { [%cal Ga5b5,Ga5b4,Re3b6] }) 12... g6! (12... Nf6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 (13... Bxc6? 14. e5 $18) 14. Bxa6 { is not really what Black wants. }) 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bh6 (14. e5 Qc7 15. exd6 Bxd6) 14... Bg5 15. Bxg5 Qxg5 16. Rxd6 Ke7 17. Rad1 Rhd8 18. Rxd8 (18. Qd2 Qxd2 19. R6xd2 Rxd2 20. Rxd2 Rc8) 18... Rxd8 19. Rxd8 Kxd8 { S.Ottesen - J.Hansen, Correspondence 2021 } *


